AGI - Giorgia. But Elly, too. And, why not, even Last. The Italian law has no special restrictions on the use of nicknames in electoral lists. In general, on the issues of attribution in the process of dismissal, the principle of the so-called favour votes, or of the conservation of the vote, that according to which, in judging the preference expressed in a ballot, we must always try to favour the will of the elector, when there is no reason to question it. And therefore, to quote the one who has reported to the general attention a practice that has existed for a long time, "there is the possibility for the elector in every election to put the name in order to extend or simplify it when it is clarified during the presentation of the application as it is replaceable". Word of Giorgia Meloni, who in Pescara, last Sunday, announcing his "discipline in the field" first person to the Europeans in June asks "the Italians to write my name, but my name of baptism". So <a> a nice 'Giorgia' on the card and via</a>.
&nbsp;
"Melons? Under the name nothing", he was less than 24 hours after the secretary of the Pd Elly Schlein. Can you vote for the Europeans for yourself by writing only 'Elly'? "That is, of course - his answer to the direct question - Elly is a nickname, because I bring the names of my two grandmothers, there is on the tab. But I always did campaigns with the surname, because I was not very well known and there was always the problem of interpretation."
<div </div
&nbsp;
A long list of precedents
The choice of the FdI leader (and the opportunity for that of the opposition) has, however, illustrious and less illustrious precedents that root in the history of the vote of the Italian Republic. Perhaps the best known is tied to Marco Pannella, Marco, in fact, in the card to be placed in the urn, not Giacinto, as the analogue wanted, as it was punctually indicated for extended in the electoral lists presented by the Radicals. There are also those who, like Jas Gawronski, elected European Parliamentary and Senator from 1979 to 2009, had no way of exploiting this possibility because it was 'called' in another way than with its name and surname, although knowing that, as he himself admitted, even his friend Gianni Agnelli would have had trouble marking the preference on the card with a Viennese surname of that fact.
&nbsp;
The use of alias, so to speak, is well known then in that of Milan, where Giuseppe Sala has always been called Beppe. And sometimes it is also a forum of controversy, as happened not long ago, in 2021, when the leader of Action, Carlo Calenda, had singular tenzone with the writer Michela Murgia because of this Cecilia Frielingsdorf, whose surname was also removed from the flyers to avoid disputes from the dismissal of the cards, invalidating the vote; a cancellation that for the writer was a serious injury of equal opportunities, cancelling a female identity.
&nbsp;
